06340nam a22008895i 9783110501933DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2018285506  a97831105019337 a10.1515/97831105019332doi  a(DE-B1597)470678  a(OCoLC)1020687564  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP158.25b.E97 2018 4aP121 7aLAN0210002bisacsh04a400#DNB00aExpanding the Lexicon :bLinguistic Innovation, Morphological Productivity, and Ludicity /cSabine Arndt-Lappe, Angelika Braun, Claudine Moulin, Esme Winter-Froemel. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VI, 304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Dynamics of Wordplay ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tExpanding the Lexicon: At the crossroads of innovation, productivity, and ludicity -- tI. Linguistic Innovation -- tExpanding the lexicon through formulaic patterns -- tComplex words in the early medieval Leges Barbarorum and their contribution to expanding the Old High German lexicon -- tFree usage of German unique components -- tII. Morphological Productivity -- tThe phonetics of newly derived words: Testing the effect of morphological segmentability on affix duration -- tHow stress reflects meaning -- tExpanding the lexicon by truncation: Variability, recoverability, and productivity -- tIII. Ludicity -- tApproaching wordplay from the angle of phonology and phonetics - examples from German -- tPlayful nonce-formations in French: Creativity and productivity -- tLudicity in lexical innovation (I) - French -- tLudicity in lexical innovation (II) - German -- tAppendix -- tList of Abstracts / Liste des résumés -- tList of Contributors and Editors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe creation of new lexical units and patterns has been studied in different research frameworks, focusing on either system-internal or system-external aspects, from which no comprehensive view has emerged. The volume aims to fill this gap by studying dynamic processes in the lexicon - understood in a wide sense as not being necessarily limited to the word level - by bringing together approaches directed to morphological productivity as well as approaches analyzing general types of lexical innovation and the role of discourse-related factors. The papers deal with ongoing changes as well as with historical processes of change in different languages and reflect on patterns and specific subtypes of lexical innovation as well as on their external conditions and the speakers' motivations for innovating. Moreover, the diffusion and conventionalization of innovations will be addressed. In this way, the volume contributes to understanding the complex interplay of structural, cognitive and functional factors in the lexicon as a highly dynamic domain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aLexical-functional grammar. 0aLinguistics. 0aPlays on words. 4aDiskurs. 4aLexikalischer Wandel. 4aProduktivität. 4aSprachliche Innovation. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Vocabulary.2bisacsh  aDiscourse.  aLexical Change.  aLinguistic Innovation.  aProductivity.1 aKremer, Anette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Angelika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArndt-Lappe, Sabine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBraun, Angelika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoulin, Claudine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary